lines.value: bastan latin alifbasi sundi ide the alphabet used by the romans consisted only of capital upper case or majuscule letters
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the lower case minuscule letters developed in the middle ages from cursive writing first as the uncial script and later as minuscule script
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the old roman letters were retained for formal inscriptions and for emphasis in written documents
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the languages that use the latin alphabet generally use capital letters to begin paragraphs and sentences and for proper nouns
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the rules for capitalization have changed over time and different languages vary somewhat in their rules for capitalization
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: english for example used to capitalize all nouns as german still does today
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the latin alphabet spread from italy along with the latin language to the lands surrounding the mediterranean sea with the expansion of the roman empire
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the eastern half of the roman empire including greece asia minor the levant and egypt continued to use greek as a lingua franca but latin was widely spoken in the western half of the empire and as the western romance languages including spanish french catalan portuguese and italian evolved out of latin they continued to use and adapt the latin alphabet
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the latin alphabet spread to the germanic peoples of northern europe with the spread of western christianity displacing the earlier runic alphabets
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: during the middle ages the latin alphabet also came into use among the western slavic peoples including the poles czechs croats slovenes and slovaks as these nations adopted roman catholicism the eastern slavs generally adopted both orthodox christianity and the cyrillic alphabet
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the baltic lithuanians and latvians as well as the non indo european finns estonians and hungarians also adopted the latin alphabet
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: by 1492 the latin alphabet was limited primarily to the roman catholic and protestant nations of western and central europe
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the orthodox christian slavs of eastern and southern europe mostly used the cyrillic alphabet and the greek alphabet was still in use by greek speakers around the eastern mediterranean
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the arabic alphabet was widespread within islam both among arabs and non arab nations like the turks and iranians
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: most of the rest of asia used a variety of brahmic alphabets or the chinese script
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: in the last 500 years the latin alphabet spread around the world
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: it spread to the americas australia and parts of asia africa and the pacific with european colonization along with the spanish portuguese english french and dutch languages
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: in the late eighteenth century the romanians adopted the latin alphabet although romanian is a romance language the romanians were predominantly orthodox christians and until the nineteenth century the church used the cyrillic alphabet
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: vietnam under french rule adapted the latin alphabet for use with the vietnamese language which had previously used chinese characters
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the latin alphabet is also used for many austronesian languages including tagalog and the other languages of the philippines and the official malaysian and indonesian languages replacing earlier arabic and indigenous brahmic alphabets
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: in 1928 as part of kemal ataturk's reforms turkey adopted the latin alphabet for the turkish language replacing the arabic alphabet
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: after the collapse of the soviet union in 1991 several of the newly independent turkic speaking republics adopted the latin alphabet replacing cyrillic
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: azerbaijan uzbekistan and turkmenia have officially adopted the latin alphabet for azeri uzbek and turkmen respectively
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: in the 1970's the peoples republic of china developed an official transliteration of mandarin chinese into the latin alphabet called pinyin although use of chinese characters is still predominant
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: in the course of its history the latin alphabet was used for new languages and therefore some new letters and diacritics were created e.g w is a letter made up from two v's or u's
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: it was added in late roman times to represent a germanic sound
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: u and j were originally not distinguished from v and i respectively
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: in old english eth o and the runic letters thorn b and wynn p were added
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: eth and thorn were replaced with th and wynn with the new letter w
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: in modern icelandic thorn and eth are still used
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the additional letters added in german are special presentations of earlier ligature forms ae → a ue → u or fs → b
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: french adds the circumflex to record elided consonants that were present in earlier forms and are often still present in the modern english cognate forms old french hostel → french hotel = english hotel or late latin pasta → middle french paste → french pate and english paste
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: some slavic languages use the latin alphabet rather than the cyrillic
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: among these polish uses a variety of digraphs with z to represent special phonetic values and a dark l l for a sound similar to w czech uses diacritics as in dvorak - the term hacek caron originates from czech
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: croatian uses carons in c s z an acute in c and a bar in d
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the languages of eastern orthodox slavs generally use cyrillic instead which is much closer to the greek alphabet
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the african language hausa uses three additional consonants ɓ ɗ and k
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: each of the iso/iec 8859-x parts encodes characters in the same way they cover the ascii range hex 20-7e plus 96 additional characters in the a0-ff range for a total of 191 characters
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the iso 8859 x sets each add the iso 646 c0 control characters from 00-1f a control character at 7f and control characters in the 80-9f range thus encompassing a total of 256 characters
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: iso 8859 1 is unique among these sets in that that its coded characters are equivalent to the first 256 code points of unicode
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: iso 8859 1 is the standard encoding used by the x window system on most unix machines
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: the legacy components of microsoft windows use by default an encoding that is a superset of iso/iec 8859-1 but differs from iso 8859 1 using displayable characters rather than control characters in the 80-9f range
lines.name: Tatar

lines.value: windows calls it ansi generically but depending on where the operating system was sold the character set will have another name e.g cp1252 in the us and western european markets with the iana approved name windows 1252
lines.name: Tatar
